19 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
20 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 70 O.S. 2021, Section 1210.508A,
21 as amended by Section 3, Chapter 411, O.S.L. 2024 (70 O.S. Supp.
22 2025, Section 1210.508A), is amended to read as follows:
23
24
HB4420 HFLR Page 3
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 Section 1210.508A. Sections 1210.508A through 1210.508H
2 1210.508J of this title shall be known and may be cited as the
3 "Strong Readers Act".
4 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 70 O.S. 2021, Section 1210.508B,
5 as amended by Section 4, Chapter 411, O.S.L. 2024 (70 O.S. Supp.
6 2025, Section 1210.508B), is amended to read as follows:
7 Section 1210.508B. A. The Legislature finds that it is
8 essential for children in the public schools to read early and well
9 in elementary school. The Legislature further finds that clear and
10 visible goals, assessments to determine the reading level at each
11 elementary school, use of a scientifically based and researched
12 methodology in reading instruction in addition to regular and
13 periodic measurements of elementary school reading improvement, and
14 accountability in each level of the educational system will result
15 in a significant increase in the number of children reading at or
16 above grade level.
17 B. The purpose of the Strong Readers Act is to ensure that
18 progression from one grade to another is determined, in part, upon
19 proficiency in reading, that school district board of education
20 policies facilitate reading instruction and intervention services to
21 address student reading needs, and that each student and his or her
22 parent or legal guardian be informed of that student's reading
23 progress. It is the intent of the Legislature that every student
24 reads at or above grade level by the end of third grade.
HB4420 HFLR Page 4
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 C. To carry out the purpose of this act, it is the intent of
2 the Legislature that the identification, instruction, and
3 intervention required under the Strong Readers Act be implemented
4 within a multitiered system of supports (MTSS) framework that
5 emphasizes strong core literacy instruction for all students and
6 provides increasing levels of instructional intensity based on
7 student need and demonstrated response to instruction.
8 D. It is further the intent of the Legislature that strong core
9 literacy instruction include explicit, systematic instruction in
10 foundational reading and writing skills, including phonological
11 awareness, decoding, encoding, spelling, sentence-level writing,
12 language development, fluency, vocabulary, and comprehension,
13 recognizing the reciprocal relationship between reading and writing
14 proficiency.
15 E. Each public school district in this state shall ensure that
16 all students receive a well-rounded education that is focused on
17 building deep foundations in reading, writing, and mathematics. The
18 State Board of Education shall encourage school districts to
19 integrate the teaching of the other curricular areas in the subject
20 matter standards adopted by the Board with the instruction of
21 reading, writing, and mathematics. All teachers of reading in the
22 public schools in this state in kindergarten through third grade
23 shall incorporate into instruction the five elements of reading
24
HB4420 HFLR Page 5
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 inst ruction which are phonological awareness, decoding, fluency,
2 vocabulary, and comprehension.
3 D. F. It is the intent of the Legislature that beginning with
4 the 2025-2026 school year, school districts and charter schools in
5 this state shall be prohibited from using the three-cueing system
6 model of teaching students to read. For the purposes of this
7 section, the "three-cueing system" means any model of teaching
8 students to read based on meaning, structure, syntax, and visual
9 cues, which may also be known as meaning, structure, and visual
10 (MSV), balanced literacy, or whole language.
11 SECTION 3. AMENDATORY 70 O.S. 2021, Section 1210.508C,
12 as last amended by Section 2, Chapter 297, O.S.L. 2025 (70 O.S.
13 Supp. 2025, Section 1210.508C), is amended to read as follows:
14 Section 1210.508C. A. To identify students who have a reading
15 deficiency or characteristics of dyslexia that lead to or cause
16 reading difficulty, each student enrolled in kindergarten and first,
17 second, and third grade in a public school in this state shall be
18 screened at the beginning, middle, and end of each school year for
19 reading skills including, but not limited to, phonological
20 awareness, decoding, fluency, vocabulary, and comprehension. A
21 screening instrument approved by the State Board of Education, in
22 consultation with the Commission for Educational Quality and
23 Accountability and the Secretary of Education, shall The Commission
24 for Educational Quality and Accountability shall evaluate and rank
HB4420 HFLR Page 6
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 up t o three screening instruments, from which the State Board of
2 Education shall select one to be utilized for the purposes of this
3 section. In determining which screening instrument to approve, the
4 State Board of Education, the Commission for Educational Quality and
5 Accountability, and the Secretary of Education shall take into
6 consideration at a minimum the following factors:
7 1. The time required to conduct the screening instrument with
8 the intention of minimizing the impact on instructional time;
9 2. The timeliness in reporting screening instrument results to
10 teachers, administrators, and parents and legal guardians of
11 students; and
12 3. The integration of the screening instrument into reading
13 curriculum; and
14 4. The ability to report all reading screening results to both
15 the State Department of Education and the Commission for Educational
16 Quality and Accountability.
17 B. Beginning in the 2025-2026 2026-2027 school year, the State
18 Board of Education shall approve no fewer than three screening
19 instruments for use at Commission for Educational Quality and
20 Accountability shall evaluate and rank up to three screening
21 instruments, from which the State Board of Education shall select
22 one for use at the beginning, middle, and end of the school year for
23 monitoring of progress and for measurement of reading skills as
24
HB4420 HFLR Page 7
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 requ ired in subsection A of this section. The selected screening
2 instruments instrument shall meet the following criteria:
3 1. Assess for phonological awareness, sound symbol recognition,
4 alphabet knowledge, rapid naming skills, decoding and encoding
5 skills, oral reading accuracy and fluency, vocabulary, and
6 comprehension as developmentally appropriate;
7 2. Document the validity and reliability of each assessment;
8 3. Can be used for identifying students who are at risk for
9 reading deficiency and progress monitoring throughout the school
10 year;
11 4. Can be used to assess students with disabilities and English
12 language learners; and
13 5. Accompanied by a data management system that provides
14 profiles of each student, class, grade level, and school building.
15 The profiles shall identify each student's instructional point of
16 need and reading achievement level. The State Board shall also
17 determine other comparable reading assessments for diagnostic
18 purposes to be used for students at risk of reading failure; and
19 6. Capable of reporting student-level data to the State
20 Department of Education.
21 C. 1. Exemptions to the screening requirements of this section
22 may be provided to students who have documented evidence that they
23 meet at least one of the following criteria as related to the
24 provision of classroom instruction:
HB4420 HFLR Page 8
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 a. the student participates in the Oklahoma Alternate
2 Assessment Program (OAAP) and is taught using
3 alternate methods,
4 b. the student's primary expressive or receptive
5 communication is sign language,
6 c. the student's primary form of written or read text is
7 Braille, or
8 d. the student's primary expressive or receptive language
9 is not English, the student is identified as an
10 English learner using a state-approved identification
11 assessment, and the student has had less than one (1)
12 school year of instruction in an English-learner
13 program.
14 2. A public school that grants an exemption pursuant to
15 paragraph 1 of this subsection shall provide ongoing evidence of
16 student progression toward English language acquisition with the
17 same frequency as administration of screening assessments. Evidence
18 may include, but not be limited to, student progression toward OAAP
19 reading essential elements, proficiency in sign language and reading
20 comprehension, and proficiency in Braille and reading comprehension.
