BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 desi gned to remediate the identified area of reading deficiency as
2 provided for in paragraph 2 of subsection F of this section;
3 4. That the parent or legal guardian shall be informed in
4 writing of the child's progress toward grade level reading at least
5 once a month and provided with strategies to assist at home;
6 5. That if the child's reading deficiency is not remediated by
7 the end of third grade, the child shall not be promoted to fourth
8 grade unless a good-cause exemption is met;
9 6. That a student who is promoted to the fourth grade for good
10 cause shall receive supplemental intensive intervention services
11 unless he or she is a student who meets the definition of a student
12 with the most significant cognitive disabilities;
13 5. Strategies 7. A description of the specific skill deficits
14 of the child and strategies for parents or legal guardians to use in
15 helping their child succeed in reading proficiency; and
16 6. 8. The grade-level performance scores of the student; and
17 9. That while the statewide English Language Arts assessment is
18 the initial determinate for promotion, students may be provided with
19 an alternative reading assessment option that is approved by the
20 State Department of Education or Commission for Educational Quality
21 and Accountability to demonstrate sufficient reading skills for
22 promotion to fourth grade.
23 I. J. No student may be assigned to a grade level based solely
24 on age or other factors that constitute social promotion.
HB4420 HFLR Page 21
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 J. K. 1. Any incoming third-grade student identified with a
2 reading deficiency shall be provided more intensified interventions
3 to remedy his or her specific reading deficiency. Intervention
4 services shall include effective instructional strategies to
5 accelerate student progress and be delivered by a teacher or
6 provider with appropriate training and demonstrated competency in
7 evidence-based reading intervention.
8 2. A review of individualized progress monitoring plans shall
9 be conducted for all incoming third-grade students identified with a
10 reading deficiency. The review shall address additional supports
11 and services the student will receive. The supports and services
12 shall include:
13 a. reading instruction and intervention services and
14 supports to correct any identified area of reading
15 deficiency,
16 b. daily targeted small group reading intervention based
17 on student need, including explicit, systematic,
18 sequential and cumulative instruction with detailed
19 explanations, extensive opportunities for guided
20 practice, and opportunities for error correction and
21 feedback, and
22 c. specialized supplemental reading intervention before
23 or after school delivered by a teacher or provider
24
